ssive mortality among enslaved Africans and European planters, soldiers, and sailors fueled the search for new healing techniques. Amerindian, African, and European knowledges competed to cure diseases emerging from the collision of peoples on newly established, often poorly supplied, plantations. But not all knowledge was equal. Highlighting the violence and fear endemic to colonial struggles, Schiebinger explores aspects of African medicine that were not put to the test, such as Obeah and vodou. This book analyzes how and why specific knowledges were blocked, discredited, or held secret.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBlacksxMedicinezWest IndiesxHistoryy18th century. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinezWest IndiesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlavesxHealth and hygienezWest IndiesxHistoryy18th century. 0aTraditional medicinezWest IndiesxHistoryy18th century. 0aTropical medicinezWest IndiesxHistoryy18th century. 4aAtlantic World. 4aCaribbean history. 4aCirculation of knowledge. 4aColonialism/Empire. 4aHuman experimentation. 4aJamaica. 4aMedical ethics. 4aRace. 4aSaint-Domingue. 4aSlavery. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360298440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602984.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles